info: This corpus is an automatically annotated version of data from the Parallel Bible Corpus (Mayer & Cysouw 2014) that has been reduced in scope for the purposes of crosslinguistic research. Metadata from the original PBC file is included in this dict for reference, as well as the license information and the automatic POS annotations. The first three characters of the filename corresponds to the ISO 639-3 code for the respective language. The `tagged` key in this dict contains a list of lists, with the first item in each sublist being the verse number (following PBC convention) and the second being a list of tuples in [word, POS] format where `unk` represents unknown tags.
license: This data is shared under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license, and can be used solely for research purposes. The data is a selection of non-contiguous verses from a translation for the purpose of crosslinguistic research. Copyright of selected verses of each translation is retained by the original copyright holders.
metadata: # copyright_long: The Mising is one of the numerous tribes in the North Eastern part of India mainly in the Dibrugarh, Lakhimpur, Sibsagar, Jorhat and Sonitpur Districts of Assam with a large concentration in the Majuli Island in Jorhat District. Their population numbered about 500,000 to 700,000. They are the third largest language group in Assam. Christian population is very small about 4000. However, the growth of the Christian Church is very encouraging. Linguistically it is closer to the Adi language group of Arunachal Pradesh. The Government of Assam approved the usage of Roman script for Mising literatures. The NRP in Mising were published in 1996. The New Testament was published in October 2001. In 2004, the Mising Church leaders submitted to the BSI a formal request for the translation of the Old Testament into Mising, which was approved in 2005. However due to nonavailability of a full time translator the project could not begin a long time. It is now in the process of the translation of the Old Testament. This translation, published by the Bible Society of India, was published in 2001. If you are interested in obtaining a printed copy, please contact the Bible Society of India at www.bsind.org
